<F P=100> Iran </F>
<H3> <TI>   Paper Questions Official Version </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  NC0802143994 Paris AFP in English 0934 GMT 8 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> NC0802143994 </F>
<F P=104>  Paris AFP </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Tehran, Feb 8 (AFP)--A radical Iranian newspaper on 
Tuesday questioned the official version of a failed bid to kill 
President 'Ali Akbar Hashemi-Rafsanjani last week. 
  A gunman fired several shots in the air as Rafsanjani 
addressed a gathering in the shrine of Ayatollah Ruhollah 
Khomeyni last Tuesday to mark the 15th anniversary of the 
Islamic revolution. 
  The official media reported that the 26-year-old gunman, 
Kurush Nik-Akhtar, fired bullets from a low-calibre colt pistol 
while standing 50 meters (yards) away from the podium. 
  "Why didn't the gunman try to get closer to the stand which 
was a simple thing to do?" the daily SALAM asked. "Why did he 
attempt to shoot from a distance where he knew he had no chance 
of hitting his target?" 
  The paper also demanded explanation on how the gunman had 
been able to pass through the shrine's security "on a day when 
so many foreign and domestic personalities were present." 
  The authorities initially played down the incident as a 
"childish affair", but later called it a "premeditated plot" 
aimed at undermining the Islamic republic. 
  Iranian Information Minister 'Ali Fallahian said Monday that 
more than 20 people had been arrested in connection with the 
shooting. They have all confessed to having "ominous and 
counter-revolutionary aims," he said. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

