<F P=100> Egypt </F>
<H3> <TI>   Minister Reiterates Role of Security Forces </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  NC0802165494 Cairo MENA in Arabic 1520 GMT 8 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> NC0802165494 </F>
<F P=104>  Cairo MENA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Arabic </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Cairo, 8 Feb (MENA)--Interior Minister Hasan al-Alfi 
has stressed that the security organs serve and protect 
everybody, both Egyptians and foreigners. He said that the 
threats made by the outlaws will not frighten the police organs, 
which have decided to confront and chase them firmly and 
decisively everywhere and at all times. 
  In his meeting with the press delegation accompanying the 
Austrian president, who is presently visiting Cairo, the 
Egyptian interior minister said that the security organs always 
have the initiative and are completely ready to confront the 
remnants of terrorism. He noted that the perpetrators of the 
incidents carried out by terrorists have been arrested and many 
crimes that were planned have been foiled. 
  Al-Alfi also noted that a large quantity of weapons and 
equipment were used in these operations, stressing that the 
crimes being perpetrated now are a reaction meant only to prove 
that they still exist. He added: We have complete information 
about them. 
  In reply to a question about the countries that support and 
sponsor the terrorist groups, the interior minister said that a 
number of countries are supporting and sponsoring the terrorists 
but he refused to divulge these countries' names, saying that 
there are diplomatic contacts to sign security agreements on the 
extradition of these elements. 
  The Egyptian interior minister denied what the human rights 
report said about torture in Egyptian prisons. He stressed that 
Egypt is a state where the rule of law prevails, which has an 
ancient civilization, and which is among the leading countries 
that care about human rights inside and outside prisons. He 
said that these criminals inflict injuries on themselves as part 
of a plan to terrorize the police commands and officers. He 
noted that the human rights report was only concerned with the 
protection of defendants but did not mention the victims of 
their operations. He added that the perpetrators of many crimes 
had been apprehended and found to have weapons and explosives 
and were brought to trial, while many policemen had been killed 
in defense of innocent citizens, legitimacy, and law and order. 
  Hasan al-Alfi stressed that cases of torture in Egypt, the 
state where the rule of law prevails, are not closed because of 
the statute of limitations. He said: If there are individual 
mistakes or excesses in the application of the law, then those 
making these mistakes and excesses are brought to account and 
punished in accordance with the law. 
  Hasan al-Alfi described the terrorist organizations as gangs 
that violate the teachings and tenets of religion, adding that 
the crimes solved confirm that the police are in control. 
  In reply to a question about the terrorists' names and 
leaders, the interior minister said that the terrorist groups' 
leaders are abroad and are known to the security organs. They 
also recruit people in the country in the name of religion, 
which is innocent of them. 
  The minister stressed that these groups' objective is to 
ruin 
development and stability in Egypt, adding that these terrorist 
groups do not exist in Egypt alone but that many countries are 
targeted by terrorism. 
  On the nationality of these terrorist elements, he said that 
they are Egyptians and their leaders abroad are recruiting some 
Egyptians and non-Egyptian under false and baseless pretexts. 
  In reply to another question about the possibility of having 
a dialogue with the terrorist groups, the interior minister 
rejected the idea of a dialogue with these terrorists groups. 
He asked: A dialogue with whom? With criminals? A dialogue 
with gangs? 
  He added that a dialogue with them is rejected because they 
are not Muslims and have no official, constitutional, or legal 
status and they are dealt with according to the law. He 
stressed his intention to continue to liquidate these elements 
and to bring them to court. 
  Hasan al-Alfi said that there are no religiously based 
parties in Egypt and that no organization or society that is 
based on religion and practices political activity is recognized. 
  The interior minister appealed to the foreign press to 
convey 
the true picture of the situation in Egypt and to expose these 
terrorist groups' practices. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

