<F P=100> ISRAEL </F>
<H3> <TI>   Right Wing Leaders Criticize Cairo Agreement </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  TA1002090794 Jerusalem Qol Yisra'el in Hebrew 0800 GMT 10 
Feb 94 </F>

<F P=103> TA1002090794 </F>
<F P=104>  Jerusalem Qol Yisra'el </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Hebrew </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] The opposition has sharply criticized the Cairo 
agreement. Likud Chairman Binyamin Netanyahu said that even if 
the loopholes in the Oslo agreement have been closed, the 
agreement with the Palestinians still entails great risks. 
  Tzomet leader Refa'el Eytan said that he does not believe 
that the Arabs will be able to keep the agreement. Eytan 
anticipates further terrorist attacks and a struggle over the 
roads. 
  Moledet chairman Rehav'am Ze'evi said that in Cairo, Peres 
and Sarid had signed a capitulation agreement which did not even 
meet Israel's security needs. 
  [Tel Aviv IDF Radio in Hebrew at 0830 GMT on 10 February 
reports that "the leaders of the Jewish settlements in the Gaza 
Strip are now holding an emergency meeting to decide upon their 
reaction to the Cairo agreement. Knesset Member Ran Kohen, the 
chairman of the Meretz Knesset faction, firmly rejected what he 
called the right- wing's intimidation campaign against the Cairo 
agreement. Kohen said that the agreement was a huge historic 
achievement for Israel and for Zionism, because in addition to 
opening the road to the implementation of peace, the 
Palestinians had for the first time accepted security 
arrangements on the basis of Israel's positions and with the 
Israeli Army retaining overall responsibility."] 

</TEXT>

