<F P=100> ISRAEL </F>
<H3> <TI>   Rabin Wants Syria To `Upgrade' Negotiators </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  TA0902171694 Jerusalem Qol Yisra'el in Hebrew 1400 GMT 9 Feb 
94 </F>

<F P=103> TA0902171694 </F>
<F P=104>  Jerusalem Qol Yisra'el </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Hebrew </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Prime Minister Yitzhaq Rabin says Israel has 
suggested that Syria upgrade its negotiating team by sending its 
foreign minister, rather that what he termed the Foreign 
Ministry pensioner. 
  In reply to a question on whether secret contacts were being 
held with Syria, the prime minister said that some things should 
be probed secretly before the sides make public commitments. 
This was how things had been done in the negotiations with 
Egypt, as well as in those with the PLO. 
  Responding to a question on whether 'Arafat had requested 
that the IDF [Israel Defense Forces] activity in the territories 
be curtailed, Yitzhaq Rabin said various requests had been 
submitted, but nothing has been promised. He maintained that 
the problem lay in people's focusing on gestures, rather than 
the agreement itself. 
  Our correspondent Qaysar Qabaha reports that the prime 
minister made these remarks in an interview with Nazareth's 
AL-SINARAH weekly. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

