<F P=100> INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> Arab-Israeli Talks </F>
<H3> <TI>   Talks To Cover Police, Amnesty Plan </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  NC1302185894 Cairo MENA in Arabic 1815 GMT 13 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> NC1302185894 </F>
<F P=104>  Cairo MENA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Arabic </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Taba, 13 Feb (MENA)--Sources in the Palestinian 
delegation to the Taba negotiations have stated that, at its 
meeting tomorrow, the Security Affairs Committee will discuss 
the details of the formation of the Palestinian police force in 
Gaza and Jericho. 
  The sources noted that the Palestinian side demands that 
this 
force be made up of 9,000 troops, while the Israeli side demands 
that it consist of 6,000 troops, including the civil defense 
force as well as the intelligence and public security services. 
  The sources added that the Civilian Affairs Committee, which 
is led by Attorney Jamil al-Tarifi on the Palestinian side, and 
by Gadi Zohar, head of the West Bank's Civil Administration, on 
the Israeli side, will resume its discussions concerning the 
transfer of powers to the Palestinians in the fields of water, 
civil planning, antiquities, electricity, communications, and 
land registration. 
  The Palestinian sources said that the Confidence-Building 
Committee, which stemmed from the Taba negotiations, will 
discuss the amnesty plan, which will include the release of all 
the Palestinian detainees in Israel at a date not later than 
July. The sources said that the number of Palestinian detainees 
is 9,000, following the Israeli authorities' recent freeing of 
some 2,000 Palestinian detainees. 
  The current round of the Taba negotiations is expected to 
last until Thursday [17 February] night. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

