<F P=100> INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> Arab-Israeli Talks </F>
<H3> <TI>   PLO's Sha'th Comments on Cairo Agreement </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  TA1002190794 Jerusalem Israel Television Channel 1 Network 
in Arabic 1700 GMT 10 Feb 94 </F>

<F P=103> TA1002190794 </F>
<F P=104>  Jerusalem Israel Television Channel 1 Network 
in Arabic 1700 GMT 10 Feb 94 </F>



<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105>Arabic </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Interview with Dr. Nabil Sha'th, chief Palestinian </F>
negotiator in the peace talks with Israel, by Me'ir Kohen in 
Cairo "this evening" -- recorded] 
  [Text] [Sha'th] In fact, this agreement is not an 
agreement in the true sense of the word, but a declaration 
resolving three major problems that obstructed these talks aimed 
at implementing the Declaration of Principles and the beginning 
of Israeli withdrawal from Gaza and Jericho. Those three 
problems relating to the crossings, the size of the Jericho 
area, and the security measures in the areas of the settlements 
and in the roads leading from the settlements to Israel 
constitute an obstacle. We announced yesterday that we had 
solved this problem and overcame this obstacle. Consequently, 
the road will be open to reaching an agreement. This is not a 
separate agreement from the Gaza-Jericho accord, nor is it a 
partial agreement, rather it is a declaration overcoming the 
major obstacles. 
  [Kohen] Will this declaration provide answers to Israeli 
security concerns and at the same time achieve Palestinian 
wishes and aspirations? 
  [Sha'th] I believe that it responds to a great many of these 
aspirations, but it does not necessarily give each party what it 
wants. This is the nature of such talks, especially as far as 
these kinds of phased talks are concerned, which seek to reach 
partial agreement on a transitional government, not on full 
sovereignty and an independent state. There is no model that 
one can follow. Therefore, we have to work out some kind of 
arrangement that realizes the Palestinian people's aspirations 
for dignity, independence, and freedom and upholds the Israelis' 
demand for security, which has always constituted an Israeli 
concern. 
  [Kohen] Dr. Nabil Sha'th, at the end of every set of 
negotiations each side calculates the losses and gains of an 
agreement. What is the Palestinian gain from the agreement 
signed in Cairo last night? 
  [Sha'th] That we implement the accord that we signed in 
Washington relatively quickly because we have lagged behind. 
Now we should end this delay so as to implement this accord. 
The beginning of an implementation of the accord will open new 
vistas to our people in the occupied Palestinian territories 
that will gradually remove from them the burden of Israeli 
occupation and achieve for them part -- part -- of their 
aspirations in governing themselves and repatriating part of the 
Palestinian people to Palestine, especially those displaced in 
1967. Consequently, the gain here is to start moving matters 
toward the realization of the Palestinian people's goals. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

