<F P=100> Tunisia </F>
<H3> <TI>   Presidential Candidate Unable To Hold News Conference </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD1102135094 Paris Radio France International in French 1230 
GMT 11 Feb 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD1102135094 </F>
<F P=104>  Paris Radio France International </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> French </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] In Tunisia, opposition leader Moncef Marzouki was 
not permitted to hold a news conference yesterday afternoon. 
Marzouki, who is an independent candidate in the presidential 
elections and former chairman of the Tunisian League for the 
Defense of Human Rights, was held for two hours at a police 
station. Marzouki wanted to explain to reporters the reasons 
for his presidential candidacy. 
  His candidacy needs sponsorship by 30 mayors or deputies. 
With one single exception, all Tunisian mayors and deputies 
belong to the Democratic Constitutional Assembly, the party in 
power. This is why Marzouki wrote to President Ben Ali, who is 
an official presidential candidate himself, to ask him to 
intervene to help him overcome the legal obstacle that is 
hindering his candidacy. 

</TEXT>

