<F P=100> Palestinian Affairs </F>
<H3> <TI>   PLO Officials To Begin Arriving in Gaza 22 Feb </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  NC1002123194 Paris AFP in English 1204 GMT 10 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> NC1002123194 </F>
<F P=104>  Paris AFP </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Gaza City, Occupied Gaza Strip, Feb 10 (AFP) -- PLO 
officials will start arriving in the occupied Gaza Strip from 
February 22 to implement the Palestinian autonomy agreement on 
the ground, a leading Palestinian figure said Thursday [10 
February]. 
  "On February 22 or 23, PLO officials will come to the Gaza 
Strip to begin to apply the Cairo agreement," Furayh 
Abu-Middayn, a member of the Palestinian delegation to the 
Middle East peace talks, told AFP. 
  "They will perhaps be accompanied by units of the Palestine 
Liberation Army," added lawyer Abu-Middayn, chairman of the Gaza 
Bar Association and a close associate of PLO chairman Yasir 
'Arafat. 
  The soldiers are to join the Palestinian police force which 
is to ensure order during autonomy. 
  The statement came after Israel and the PLO settled their 
differences on security aspects of the September 13 Declaration 
of Principles for Palestinian autonomy. 
  The security deal opens the way for autonomy to be 
implemented, but Israeli Prime Minister Yitzhaq Rabin has warned 
it will take at least another month to sort out other issues, 
such as the economic side of self-rule. 

</TEXT>

