<F P=100> Palestinian Affairs </F>
<H3> <TI>   PLO Leaders, Opposition Analyze Cairo Agreement </TI></H3>
<H4>   Al-Najjab Urges Rejection of Accord </H4>
<F P=102> JN1402114094 Amman AL-RA'Y in Arabic 14 Feb 94 p 27 </F>
<F P=103> JN1402114094 </F>
<F P=104>  Amman AL-RA'Y </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Arabic </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by 'Awdah 'Awdah] </F>
  [Text] PLO Executive Committee member Sulayman al-Najjab 
refused to participate in the Executive Committee meeting which 
began in the Tunisian capital last evening. The meeting was 
called for by Palestinian President Yasir 'Arafat. 
  In an exclusive statement to AL-RA'Y, al-Najjab said he did 
not attend the meeting to protest the manner in which the 
Executive Committee was treated. He said the decisions of the 
committee and the instructions it gave to the Palestinian 
negotiating delegation were not respected. The Cairo agreement 
between 'Arafat and Peres was a deviation from all these 
decisions and instructions. Al- Najjab urged the Executive 
Committee members to reject the Cairo agreement because it 
entrenches the Israeli understanding of the Declaration of 
Principles. 
  Al-Najjab, who is the representative of the Palestinian 
People's Party [PPP] in the Executive Committee, warned against 
continuing the current policy of dealing with the negotiating 
process, which is proceeding without any terms of reference and 
any clear negotiating plan that is committed to the Palestinian 
understanding of the Oslo agreement, whose objective is to 
secure Israel's withdrawal from all Palestinian territories 
occupied in 1967 and to guarantee the Palestinian people's right 
to self-determination. 
  Al-Najjab warned against the danger of unilateral and 
unstudied decisions, and against responding to pressures 
employed by foreign parties that do not take into account the 
legitimate rights of the Palestinian people. 
  Al-Najjab called anew for respecting the Executive 
Committee's decisions and for organizing its action as the 
higher Palestinian authority, including its decision to form a 
body responsible for negotiations that no party can overstep. 
He also called for adopting a Palestinian negotiating plan that 
reflects the Palestinian militant concept of the Oslo agreement, 
and for assigning qualified Palestinian politicians the task of 
implementing this plan. 
  Following the signing of the Cairo agreement, the PPP's 
Political Bureau issued a statement, a copy of which was 
received by AL-RA'Y. The statement urged the Executive Committee 
to reject this agreement and to lay down new bases for the 
negotiations aimed to realize the legitimate rights of the 
Palestinian people. 
  The statement described the agreement as disappointing to 
the 
popular aspirations, and said the warnings expressed by the PPP 
when it conditionally accepted the Oslo agreement were 
legitimate. Since the beginning, the PPP has called for giving 
the Oslo agreement a militant concept and not to view it as a 
petition presented to the Israeli authorities. The PPP also 
called for working out a clear negotiating plan, for high 
Palestinian performance, and for a fixed political authority. 
These demands ensure that the Oslo agreement will be the 
beginning of the march toward independence, and prevent the 
Israeli concept of implementation of the agreement, which would 
entrench the occupation. 
  The Cairo agreement is closer to the Israeli understanding 
of 
the Oslo agreement. It adopted the Israeli concept of security, 
which is an expansionist one that seeks to entrench settlements. 
This concept conflicts with the natural concept of security as 
stipulated in Resolution 242, which is based on the 1967 borders. 

</TEXT>

