<F P=100> Palestinian Affairs </F>
<H3> <TI>   PLO Leaders, Opposition Analyze Cairo Agreement </TI></H3>
<H4>   'Abd-al-Shafi on Limits to Accord </H4>
<F P=102> NC1102161394 Paris AFP in English 1528 GMT 11 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> NC1102161394 </F>
<F P=104>  Paris AFP </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Gaza City, Occupied Gaza Strip, Feb 11 (AFP) -- 
Haydar 'Abd-al-Shafi, a former chief Palestinian negotiator, 
said Friday [11 February] the Israeli-PLO security accord signed 
in Cairo did not cover issues essential to achieving a just 
peace in the Middle East. 
  "This is an accord on issues which are unimportant in 
relation to the ultimate goal of achieving a just peace," the 
former chief Palestinian negotiator at the Washington peace 
talks told AFP. 
  "The key issue to be resolved, which may lead to a just 
peace, is that of ending the (Israeli) settlements in Jerusalem 
and the rest of the occupied territories," he said. 
  'Abd-al-Shafi earlier told the Arabic daily Al-Quds: 
"Palestine existed before this agreement, and will exist after 
it, but the accord will not allow Palestine ever to appear on 
the map of the Middle East." 
  He was commenting on PLO chief Yasir 'Arafat's statement 
after signing the accord that the name of Palestine had returned 
to the map of the Middle East. 
  Meanwhile Sufyan Abu-Zayda, a representative of 'Arafat's 
Fatah movement in the occupied Gaza Strip, told AFP the accord 
"only deals with a tiny part of our demands, and will not last 
long if the occupation and settlements remain." 
  The Islamic Resistance Movement HAMAS, which is opposed to 
the Israeli-PLO autonomy deal signed in Washington on September 
13, said the Cairo security agreement was "worthless," and 
"fulfils Israeli conditions." 
  "The settlements will remain a breeding ground for 
provocation and tension, and will allow Israel to justify its 
persecution of the Palestinians," said HAMAS official Khalid 
al-Hindi. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

