<H3> <TI>   PLO Leaders, Opposition Analyze Cairo Agreement </TI></H3>
<H4>   Former Communist Party Rejects Agreement </H4>
<F P=102> TA1302202494 Jerusalem Israel Television Channel 1 Network 
in Hebrew 1800 GMT 13 Feb 94 </F>

<F P=103> TA1302202494 </F>
<F P=104>  Jerusalem Israel Television Channel 1 Network 
in Hebrew 1800 GMT 13 Feb 94 </F>



<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105>Hebrew </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] The Palestinian People's Party [PPP], formerly the 
Communist Party in the territories, announced tonight that it is 
rejecting the Cairo agreement and is demanding that the PLO 
Executive Committee be convened to reject the agreements reached 
by Peres and 'Arafat. Ghassan al-Khatib, one of the party 
leaders, told our correspondent Linda Sherzer that he did not 
believe 'Arafat would be able to muster a majority for the 
agreement in the Executive Committee. 
  The PPP contends that the Cairo agreement is based on the 
Israeli demands, and the arrangements stipulated in it are 
liable to last long after the interim period. The party, which 
supported the Oslo agreement, is particularly opposed to the 
arrangements at the border terminals and the security roads 
leading to the Gaza Strip settlements. 

</TEXT>

