<H3> <TI>   Foreign Minister Comments on NATO, Bosnia </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  NC1102124994 Cairo MENA in Arabic 1046 GMT 11 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> NC1102124994 </F>
<F P=104>  Cairo MENA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Arabic </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Cairo, 11 Feb (MENA)--Foreign Minister 'Amr Musa has 
said Egypt believes the use of force against the Serbs in Bosnia 
is stipulated in a Security Council resolution and requires no 
further discussion. 
  Commenting today on NATO's decision to give the Serbs 10 
days 
to withdraw or face an air strike and on Russia's request for an 
urgent Security Council meeting to discuss the demilitarization 
of Sarajevo, Musa said Egypt and the Islamic countries will 
oppose any attempt to hinder the end of the Serbian aggression. 
He explained that if the attempts to delay things continue, 
then the arms embargo on the Bosnian Muslims must be lifted. 
  He stressed that UN Secretary General Dr. Butrus 
Butrus-Ghali 
has a Security Council mandate to use force to protect UN forces 
and populated areas and that this mandate is sufficient, 
especially so in light of NATO's offer to use its resources in 
this regard. 
  Foreign Ministry sources said 'Amr Musa has asked Dr. Nabil 
al- 'Arabi, Egypt's permanent delegate at the United Nations, to 
convey to the UN secretary general and Security Council 
president Egypt's viewpoint on attempts to delay the NATO 
decision. 
  The sources added that Musa asked Egypt's permanent delegate 
at the United Nations to hold consultations with the Islamic 
countries' Liaison Group to adopt a clear stance on the issue. 

</TEXT>

