<F P=100> ARAB AFRICA </F>
<F P=101> Egypt </F>
<H3> <TI>   Papers Examines, Lauds PLO-Israeli Peace Accord </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  NC1102092294 Cairo MENA in Arabic 0702 GMT 11 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> NC1102092294 </F>
<F P=104>  Cairo MENA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Arabic </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Cairo, 11 Feb MENA)--The Cairo newspapers today 
stated that the will of peace has imposed itself on the Middle 
East and that intentions of armed conflict have receded after 
Palestinian president Yasir 'Arafat and Israeli Foreign Minister 
Shim'on Peres signed the Cairo Agreement to implement the 
Gaza-Jericho Accord. 
  AL-AKHBAR said the agreement will help toward signing a 
final 
accord between 'Arafat and Israeli Prime Minister Yitzhaq Rabin 
to implement the Declaration of Principles, which everyone hopes 
will end the tension and bloody conflict prevailing in the 
region for approximately 50 years. 
  The paper called on Israel to eliminate any potential 
obstacles that might mar the tranquility of the negotiations' 
final phase or that might impede the required measures to 
implement the accord. 
  The paper warned against building new settlements that will 
create disputes and a conflict of authority in these territories 
at a time when understanding and cooperation are needed to 
streamline the transfer of power in an atmosphere of tranquility 
and coexistence. 
  AL-JUMHURIYAH praised President Husni Mubarak's efforts to 
bring the Palestinian and Israeli views closer until the Cairo 
Declaration was signed. 
  It said: Egypt hosted Palestinian and Israeli negotiating 
delegations and was open to a difficult dialogue between the two 
sides at a crucial moment and while the Palestinian and Israeli 
negotiators faced a difficult situation. The Palestinian 
negotiator relied on vast Egyptian experience of dialogue and 
formulating negotiating positions. 
  AL-JUMHURIYAH expressed the hope that the peace process will 
extend east to include Jordan and Israel and north to include 
Syria, Lebanon, and Israel. 
  AL-AHRAM emphasized that Egyptian diplomacy did all it could 
to push negotiations between the two sides to the shore of 
safety in line with its historical and cultural role in the 
region as the largest Arab country. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

