<F P=100> Libya </F>
<H3> <TI>   Al-Qadhdhafi Questions Clinton's Report to Congress </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD1202165394 Tripoli JANA in Arabic 1545 GMT 12 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD1202165394 </F>
<F P=104>  Tripoli JANA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Arabic </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Tripoli, 12 Feb, JANA -- The brother leader of the 
revolution has made the following statement to JANA: The world 
laughs from ear to ear when it hears the American President's 
report to Congress to the effect that Libya represents an 
extraordinary threat to the United States. The American 
President himself does not believe in what he presented to the 
Congress, because if Libya was like a threat, then America would 
not have been able to treat it in this inhuman way, but it seems 
that the American President is obliged to say this to Congress 
for several reasons: First: He himself is a victim of 
aggressive imperialist circles and because he is part of the 
their game and is under their pressure. 
  Second: He thinks of America's regime as being dictatorial 
in 
accordance with the emergency law that allows the American 
President to rule in a completely dictatorial manner if 
America's interests abroad are threatened. This was the very 
pretext of Reagan when he wanted to shed the blood of Libyan 
children and when he wanted to rule America with absolute and 
autocratic rule for eight years -- this was in fact what he 
achieved. 
  Third: Orders may have been issued from Tel Aviv to the 
White House to make the above statement, and this is the most 
probable. In all cases, the American President must prove this 
to the United Nations to whom Libya will necessarily have 
recourse for investigations into this serious accusation. Or is 
it congratulations from the American President to the Libyan 
people on the occasion of Ramadan? On a personal level, it 
might be a reply to the condolences that al-Qadhdhafi sent to 
him following the death of his mother, although most analysts 
believed that there was a typing mistake and the one intended 
was Japan and not Libya. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

