<H3> <TI>   Assembly Speaker, Envoy Note Embargo </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  JN1002204294 Baghdad INA in Arabic 2005 GMT 10 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> JN1002204294 </F>
<F P=104>  Baghdad INA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Arabic </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Baghdad, 10 Feb (INA) -- National Assembly speaker 
Sa'di Mahdi Salih today received Asif Zardari, Pakistani Prime 
Minister Benazir Bhutto's personal envoy to leader President 
Saddam Husayn, and his accompanying delegation. 
  The National Assembly speaker asserted that Iraq's friends 
are dutybound to work and pressure the Security Council to lift 
the unjust embargo against the Iraqi epople, now that all its 
justifications no longer exist. 
  Salih also valued Pakistan's positive stands at the Security 
Council toward Iraq's just cause. He pointed to the deep 
historical ties and good relations between Iraq and Pakistan. 
  Asif Zardari said there is a need to end the suffering of 
the 
Iraqi people as a result of the unfair economic embargo. He 
said there is no justification for the continuation of the 
embargo. 
  The two officials stressed the need to enhance parliamentary 
ties between the two countries by exchanging visits, forming 
friendship committees, unifying positions, and doing what is in 
the interest of the Iraqi and Pakistani peoples. 

</TEXT>

