<F P=100> IRAQ </F>
<H3> <TI>   Envoy Views Talks </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  JN1402110194 Baghdad AL-THAWRAH in Arabic 11 Feb 94 pp 1, 2 </F>
<F P=103> JN1402110194 </F>
<F P=104>  Baghdad AL-THAWRAH </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Arabic </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [By Khalid 'Abd-al-Rahim] </F>
  [Text] Asif Ali Zardari, personal envoy of Pakistani Prime 
Minister Benazir Bhutto, has said the three-year-old embargo 
against the Iraqi people is an inhuman crime committed by 
countries that claim to be civilized and to care about human 
rights. 
  In a statement to AL-THAWRAH, Zardari said the fact that the 
embargo has been in place for more than three years confirms the 
barbarity of these nations, which are killing the elderly and 
children through this embargo. The nations which claim to be 
civilized should reconsider their stands and heed international 
appeals for an immediate lifting of the embargo against the 
struggling Iraqi people. They should also have a humanitarian 
view and translate it into action. 
  On the effects of the embargo on the economy of Pakistan, 
Zardari said Pakistan had previously broad trade and economic 
interests with Iraq and the other Arab states. The embargo has 
greatly affected trade in Pakistan. We have lost a great deal 
due to the embargo's impact on trade and economic ties which had 
earlier revived the Pakistani economy. The embargo has harmed 
these interests and inflicted great harm on the Pakistani 
economy, he said. 
  Assessing Iraqi-Pakistani ties, the Pakistani envoy said: 
Iraqi-Pakistani relations date back thousands of years. They 
have always been strong and close. Since a friend in need is a 
friend indeed, Pakistan had to side with Iraq because it is 
experiencing difficult circumstances that require extending all 
kinds of support to it. 
  I also consider Iraq my first country because I come from 
the 
Sind province, which shares deep-rooted relations with Iraq 
since the Islamic conquest. Therefore, the purpose of our visit 
is to enhance relations between the two Muslim peoples and 
friendly countries. 
  On his talks with Iraqi officials, the Pakistani envoy said: 
The talks were conducted in a cordial, frank atmosphere. We 
exchanged views to promote cooperation in the interest of our 
two peoples. 
  Asif Zardari handed a written message to Prime Minister 
Ahmad 
Khudayyir on 9 February addressed from Benazir Bhutto to 
President Saddam Husayn. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

