<F P=100> ISRAEL </F>
<H3> <TI>   Peres `Seems Quite Pessimistic' About Syrian Track </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  TA1302173494 Jerusalem Qol Yisra'el in Hebrew 1605 GMT 13 
Feb 94 </F>

<F P=103> TA1302173494 </F>
<F P=104>  Jerusalem Qol Yisra'el </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Hebrew </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by political correspondent Shlomo Raz] </F>
  [Text] Foreign Minister Shim'on Peres was asked a few 
minutes ago to comment on his proposal to Syria to engage in 
talks on more than one track and on the Syrian rejection of this 
proposal. Peres said there is no indication that Syria has 
softened its demands from Israel. Peres seems quite pessimistic 
concerning the prospects of advancing the negotiations with 
Syria. He said their acceptance of his suggestion to expand the 
Syrian-Israeli negotiations to several tracks would have 
indicated that they seriously meant to promote the peace 
process. For Peres, their rejection of his proposal was another 
unfavorable sign of Syria's intentions. 
  [Jerusalem Qol Yisra'el in Hebrew at 1700 GMT on 13 February 
cites Peres as saying that "Israel prefers a confederation 
between the Palestinian entity and Jordan. If such a 
confederation is not established, conflicts may arise between 
Jordan and the Palestinian entity, entangling Israel."] 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

