<F P=100> ISRAEL </F>
<H3> <TI>   Defense Official: Israel Obtained `Everything' Wanted </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  NC1002152294 Paris AFP in English 1432 GMT 10 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> NC1002152294 </F>
<F P=104>  Paris AFP </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Jerusalem, Feb 10 (AFP) -- Israel obtained 
everything it wanted from the security deal agreed with the 
Palestinians in Cairo, Defence Ministry spokesman Oded Ben Ami 
[spelling as received] said 10 February. 
  "The very fact of reaching an agreement is in itself 
positive," he told AFP. "That shows that we got what we wanted." 
  The Ma'ariv newspaper headlined: "Security top brass happy, 
'All our main demands have been accepted'." 
  The daily quoted triumphant security officials 
congratulating 
themselves on the pact signed by PLO chairman Yasir 'Arafat and 
Israeli Foreign Minister Shim'on Peres on Wednesday [9 February] 
night. 
  Israel keeps control of the border and crossing points, 
Jewish settlements and roads leading to them for the five-year 
interim period of autonomy. 
  Ben Ami said Israeli and Palestinian delegations would next 
week resume talks on the military, civilian and economic aspects 
of autonomy, in the Egyptian Red Sea resort of Taba and in 
Paris, in a bid to seal an overall agreement to launch self-rule. 
  "We are now going to try to put into practice the principles 
expressed and signed in Cairo. A lot of questions remain to be 
answered," Ben Ami said. 

</TEXT>

