<F P=100> Sri Lanka </F>
<H3> <TI>   Government Troops Destroy Tamil Guerrilla Camp </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  BK1402113694 Hong Kong AFP in English 0602 GMT 14 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> BK1402113694 </F>
<F P=104>  Hong Kong AFP </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Colombo, Feb 14 (AFP) -- Government troops Monday 
concluded a limited weekend offensive against Tamil guerrillas 
in northeastern Sri Lanka, destroying a rebel camp and seizing 
dozens of anti-personnel mines, officials said. 
  About a thousand troops backed by air and sea cover returned 
to base in coastal Trincomalee following the operation over the 
weekend against the Liberation Tigers of Tamil Eelam (LTTE) 
rebels in the region, officials said. 
  Troops destroyed an abandoned LTTE camp that included 15 
well- fortified bunkers and ten small accomodation units, a 
military spokesman said. They also recovered about 50 
anti-personnel mines from the rebel camp, he said. 
  "The Tigers left the camp to avoid confronting advancing 
troops. One soldier was wounded when he stepped on an 
anti-personnel mine," the spokesman said. 
  The latest offensive was part of a military campaign to 
flush 
out LTTE rebels in parts of the island's north and the entire 
east ahead of key local government elections in the region on 
March 1. 
  The LTTE, which is fighting for a separate state in the 
northeast for Sri Lanka's minority Tamils, have vowed to disrupt 
the polls in northern Vavuniya, in Trincomalee and the 
neighbouring districts of Batticaloa and Ampara. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS3-34734 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drnes030_s_94002" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-NES-94-030 </AU>
Document Type:Daily Report 
<DATE1>  14 Feb 1994 </DATE1>

