<F P=100> Iran </F>
<H3> <TI>   President's Brother Resigns Post Heading Radio, TV </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  NC1202172194 Paris AFP in English 1600 GMT 12 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> NC1202172194 </F>
<F P=104>  Paris AFP </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Tehran, Feb 12 (AFP) -- President 'Ali Akbar 
Hashemi-Rafsanjani's brother has resigned as head of Iran's 
state radio and television (IRIB), the daily KEYHAN reported 
Saturday. 
  Mohammad Hashemi, who was to leave his post on Saturday 
after 
12 years, is to be replaced by the Minister of Culture and 
Islamic Guidance 'Ali Larijani, it said. 
  The head of the ministry's publication bureau, Ahmad 
Pur-Nejati, has been chosen to serve as interim culture 
minister, the paper added. 
  IRIB has come under mounting conservative criticism. 
  Parliament's culture subcommittee issued a lengthy report in 
November which said many programmes had nothing to do with Islam 
or the Islamic revolution, and spread "un-Islamic" ideas, 
particularly among the young. 
  The report prompted a strong reaction from Hashemi, who 
accused the hardliners of promoting "stone-age" thinking. The 
conservatives hit back accusing IRIB's head of defaming 
parliament. 
  Newspapers said in December that Hashemi could face legal 
proceedings. 
  IRIB has been under the direct supervision of the country's 
spiritual guide since the 1979 Islamic revolution, 

</TEXT>

