<F P=100> ARABIAN PENINSULA </F>
<F P=101> Yemen </F>
<H3> <TI>   Official Comments on Hopes for Accord </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  JN1002155194 Sanaa Yemeni Republic Radio Network in Arabic 
1200 GMT 10 Feb 94 </F>

<F P=103> JN1002155194 </F>
<F P=104>  Sanaa Yemeni Republic Radio Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Arabic </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Excerpt] Brother 'Abd-al-'Aziz 'Abd-al-Ghani, member of 
the Presidential Council; and brothers Dr. Hasan Muhammad Makki, 
first deputy prime minister; Brigadier General Yahya 
al-Mutawakkil, the minister of interior; and Muhammad Hasan 
Dammaz, minister of local administration today attended the 
graduation ceremony of the first group of district security 
officers and of other groups of graduates from training courses 
organized by the high police institute. 
  During the ceremony, which began with a recital of verses 
from the Koran, brother 'Abd-al-'Aziz 'Abd-al-Ghani, member of 
the Presidential Council, delivered a speech in which he 
congratulated the graduates on their success in the course and 
on the approach of the holy month of Ramadan, wishing the Yemeni 
people many happy returns full of good fortune, welfare, and 
happiness. 
  He said the Political Forces Dialogue Committee today will 
finalize arrangements for the signing of the document of pledge 
and accord which the political forces completed last month. He 
hoped that the political leadership will sign this document 
within a week from today. This document was completed after a 
lengthy dialogue among the political forces because of the 
crisis which our country has been facing since 9 August 1993. 
  The brother member of the Presidential Council said that the 
crisis had negative effects on the various political, economic, 
and social fields, noting that it resulted in many things we 
hoped will never happen and the consquences of which will be 
assumed by those who caused it. He hoped that after the signing 
of the document, our country will enter a new stage of security, 
stability, and serious action in order to compensate for the 
events of the past period in which matters reached a state of 
paralysis in all parts of the country. 
  He added that thanks to God almighty and Yemeni wisdom, the 
Yemeni people and their political forces resorted to dialogue as 
a means to resolve problems. He noted that the dialogue led to 
this document to which we are committed and which we will 
implement, in text and spirit, because it contains many 
guidelines for tackling a number of political issues in local 
government, economic and security issues, the Armed Forces, and 
other issues that were the cause of this crisis. 
  Dr. 'Abd-al-Ghani hoped that the graduates will perform 
their 
duty in this important security field with absolute sincerity 
and dedication. He noted that all our Yemeni people and those 
working at the Interior Ministry, who shoulder a primary 
responsibility of maintaining the country's security and 
stability, should pay more attention to security in our country. 
  Concluding his speech, he congratulated the graduates and 
valued the teaching staff's great efforts and sincere work to 
render this course a success. [passage omitted] 

</TEXT>

