<F P=100> SOUTH ASIA </F>
<F P=101> Iran </F>
<H3> <TI>   UN Envoy Comments on Bosnian Serbs, NATO Air Strikes </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD1502085594 Tehran IRNA in English 0709 GMT 15 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD1502085594 </F>
<F P=104>  Tehran IRNA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] United Nations, New York, Feb. 15, IRNA -- Iran's 
envoy to the United Nations Monday stressed that in case Serb 
forces refused to observe the NATO deadline, the North Atlantic 
Treaty Organization must implement its threats against the Serbs. 
  Following the Serbs shelling of a trade center in Sarajevo 
in 
late January which claimed the lives of 68 people and over 200 
others were wounded, in a 10-day deadline last Wednesday the 
NATO urged the Serbs to withdraw their heavy arms from the 
vicinity of Sarajevo. It warned that in case the Serbs 
refrained from doing so NATO forces would strike them by air. 
  Iran's permanent representative at the United Nations Kamal 
Kharrazi in his remarks at the open session of the Security 
Council said that the recent moves to lift the seige of Sarajevo 
fell short of expectations. 
  He stressed that overall efforts should be made to ensure 
that all provisions of the ultimatum are met by the Serbs. 
  "In the event the ultimatum is violated, either through 
further shelling or failure to fully withdraw the Serbian heavy 
weaponry by the deadline, the air strikes must be automatically 
initiated," he said. 
  Kharrazi called on Security Council to allow Bosnia and 
those 
prepared to help the beseiged republic to take action under 
Article 51 of the UN Charter in individual and collective 
self-defence. 
  "Under the present circumstances, the least the 
international 
community can do is to lift the siege of Sarajevo and other 
cities and to lift the unjust arms embargo against the republic 
of Bosnia and Herzegovina." 
  He voiced concern over the efforts made by some powers to 
press the Bosnian Government to accept a so-called peace saying 
that it "will be the beginning of a more tragedy and ethnic 
cleansing." 
  He stressed that imposition of any settlement on the Bosnian 
Government would be "militarily unenforceable and morally 
unacceptable to the international community." 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

