<F P=100> JORDAN </F>
<H3> <TI>   French Foreign Minister Holds Talks in Amman </TI></H3>
<H4>   Juppe Holds News Conference </H4>
<F P=102> JN1302145794 Amman Radio Jordan Network in Arabic 1400 GMT 
13 Feb 94 </F>

<F P=103> JN1302145794 </F>
<F P=104>  Amman Radio Jordan Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Arabic </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] French Foreign Minister Alain Juppe has stressed the 
firmness and depth of the long-standing relations between Jordan 
and France. He reiterated France's appreciation of His Majesty 
King Husayn's wise and moderate views on many international and 
regional issues. 
  Speaking at a news conference in Amman today, Juppe said he 
came to Jordan and the region with two objectives. He said his 
objectives are represented by reiterating France's commitment to 
the peace initiative in the region, signed by the Palestinians 
and the Israelis on 13 September, as well as by expressing 
appreciation of Jordan's contribution as represented by the 
signing of the Jordanian-Israeli agenda on 14 September. 
Furthermore, he added, the visit is designed to stress the ties 
of friendship and cooperation between the two friendly countries 
in various fields. 
  Juppe said France is concerned about helping Jordan 
reschedule its debts during the upcoming Paris Club meeting. He 
said an agreement had been reached with the Jordanian officials 
to review all aspects of the agreement signed between the two 
countries in 1965 in order to expand it and develop it to be 
more comprehensive and more effective within the framework of 
the joint committee between the two countries. This, Juppe 
added, will foster greater cooperation, noting the French desire 
to increase cooperation within the civil service. 
  The French foreign minister said that during his talks with 
Jordanian officials, he became aware of the difficulties facing 
the Jordanian economy as a result of the siege of the Port of 
al-'Aqabah. He stressed France's readiness to alleviate the 
burden of the embargo on Jordan without detriment to the 
objectives of the sanctions. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

